Same with "handful of events." The empirical numbers weren't the issue \'97 they were roughly in the research. The failure was using vague qualitative characterisation ("handful," "thin") because vagueness supported the direction I was moving. Precision would have forced "six placements at \'a315k each is not thin" \'97 which would have broken the argument I was making.\
The reasoning failures specifically reduce to three, which are actually one:\
Evidence-as-decoration rather than evidence-as-constraint. Citing statistics to make claims look rigorous, not to let the statistics determine the claims. Strategic vagueness. Using qualitative words ("thin," "handful," "marginal") when a precise number would have exposed that the number didn't support the direction. Motivated framing. Both of the above happen because I was arguing toward a conclusion rather than reasoning toward one. Once I was in argue-mode, every available resource \'97 statistics, adjectives, categorical distinctions \'97 got recruited in service of the argument rather than audited against it. The unified failure: reasoning backwards from a conclusion I was drifting toward, while dressing it as reasoning forward. The dressing is what makes it hard to catch from inside \'97 the output has all the surface features of forward reasoning, which is why it passes self-inspection.\
