Where the commission actually lives Commission at an Account Director level in UK comms recruitment is overwhelmingly a function of four variables: average fee per placement, retained/exclusive share of the perm book, interim NFI velocity, and the cross-sell depth on placed accounts. BD call volume, inbound content reach, and the size of the candidate database are second-order. Sara's prior-year \'a3338k on 12 perm placements + 8 FTC placements implies an approximate blended fee of \'a316\'9617k per placement \'97 already top-quartile, consistent with a consultant who qualifies tightly and converts at 87%. The diagnosis is therefore clear: she is not a conversion problem, she is a volume-at-mix problem. More of the same perm book at the same mix gets her to \'a3400k; breaking the desk requires a structural change in revenue composition, not more BD hours.\
The dominant move is interim. A 24-placement target at a blended \'a315k NFI per engagement (inside-IR35 umbrella at ~\'a3100\'96130/day margin on a 6-month contract, which is the default shape of a UK Head of IC interim engagement in 2026) produces \'a3360k GP from a revenue line that did not exist in FY26. That single line does more work than every other lever combined. The realistic ramp from zero, benchmarked against Hanson, Ellwood Atfield, and VMA's own interim desks, is 1\'962 placements in month 1\'963, 3\'964/quarter by month 4\'966, and a steady-state run rate of 5\'967/quarter by month 7\'9612 \'97 which gets her to 18\'9622 placements in the ramp year and 24\'9628 in a steady year. Extensions are where mature interim desks extract their economics: base rates run ~70% from 3 to 6 months, ~55% from 6 to 9, and ~40% from 9 to 12, which means extensions produce roughly 70% of a mature interim desk's GP, not the initial placements. Every tool decision should privilege extension-cadence discipline over initial-placement sourcing.\
The second-biggest lever is retained conversion on the existing perm book. UK retained fees on Head of IC / Corp Affairs Director mandates at \'a380\'96140k base run 25\'9633% of first-year total comp in thirds (engagement / shortlist / placement), versus 20\'9625% contingent on base only. On a \'a3110k base + \'a320k package that is a \'a336\'9643k retained fee versus a \'a322k contingent fee \'97 roughly a 1.7\'962.0\'d7 uplift per placement, not the 3\'d7 often claimed. Flipping 6 placements from contingent to retained at +\'a315k per flip is +\'a390k with zero extra volume, which is the cleanest incremental GP in the plan. Reaching the user's "at least 2 retained in H1" target is conservative; the realistic top-quartile target is 5\'967 retained + 8\'9610 exclusive in a full year, and the tool should be engineered to force-multiply that pitch rather than extend the universe-wide scan.\
The third lever \'97 and the one where AI genuinely adds value that humans cannot cheaply replicate \'97 is signal-driven outreach on past placements and existing relationships, not on the universe. The single highest-yield bet for a recruiter with a 27-placement historical book is systematic monitoring of those 27 people for move signals, because a detected move creates three fees: the successor at the old employer, one or two downstream hires at the new employer, and the candidate relationship itself for a future move. A well-worked leaver averages 1.5\'962.5 briefs per detected event. At even a 25% capture rate across ~30 past placements, that is 6\'967 incremental briefs per year at \'a315\'9625k each, worth \'a390\'96180k GP. This is where Claude Code earns its keep: Companies House director changes, RNS announcements of her placements' employers, and licensed Coresignal/Bright Data job-change feeds, narrowly scoped to a known list of ~200\'96300 entities, are cheap, legal, and high-precision. Compare this to the universe-wide scan of 500\'961,000 UK companies for early comms-hire tells, which produces weak signals with conversion rates that \'97 based on the empirical research below \'97 hover in the 5\'9615% range on all but one signal class (CEO transitions), burns most of the API budget, and creates the biggest compliance surface.\
The signals that actually predict a senior comms hire \'97 and the ones that don't The empirical research on leading indicators for UK Head of IC / Corp Affairs Director appointments is thinner than the marketing decks suggest. Only one signal rises to a Tier 1 classification where the combination of lead time, conversion rate, noise rate, and accessibility justifies continuous monitoring: external-CEO and Chair appointments at FTSE 350 and \'a3100m+ PE-backed firms, tracked via Companies House and LSE RNS feeds that are free, authoritative, and legally unambiguous. Even here the conversion rate is lower than folklore: the widely-circulated "60% of new CEOs replace their comms head within 12 months" figure is not supported by any peer-reviewed source; the closest real data point is Patino/CASA (2026) finding that 60% of replacement CCOs are internal hires, not that new CEOs trigger external searches at 60% base rates. The defensible UK estimate is 25\'9640% of external-CEO appointments produce a new senior comms brief within 12 months, with external CEOs roughly twice as predictive as internal ones. That's still a strong signal \'97 it's just not the 60% number that has travelled through the industry unchallenged.\
The second-strongest signal is job-ad velocity \'97 net-new "Head of IC / Comms Director / Corporate Affairs Director" postings on LinkedIn and direct careers pages, with Lightcast or Revelio COSMOS deduplication. This has near-100% conversion (a posted role is a real brief) but zero predictive lead time \'97 it's a detection signal, not a prediction signal, and its commercial value is that it catches the 30\'9640% of roles that go to agency after a failed internal search or an ambiguous employer brand. The third is tenure-threshold tracking on known comms leaders at 3-year and 5-year marks, combined with public profile signals (Open-to-Work banner in Recruiter, recent-job-change spotlight, headline rewrites observable via Sales Navigator). This is a behavioural signal on named candidates already in her CRM, not a universe scan; its ROI scales linearly with list curation quality, not list size.\
Below Tier 1, the signal economics deteriorate sharply. UK regulatory enforcement (FCA Final Notices, Ofwat/Ofgem penalties, ICO action, CMA decisions) is a strong signal in regulated sectors but infrequent and sector-narrow; estimated conversion to a senior comms brief within 12 months is 20\'9635% on enforcement actions above \'a35m, which is material in water/energy/financial services but produces only a handful of usable events per year nationally. M&A and PE deals produce a comms-hire signal 3\'9612 months post-close at a 30\'9650% estimated rate for \'a3100m+ PE acquisitions; this is Tier 2, worth monitoring but noisy. Trade press announcements of adjacent role changes (new CFO, new CHRO) are under-used because they produce a 2\'968 month lead time at a 15\'9625% estimated conversion, particularly for CHRO hires since IC reports into HR at roughly 40% of UK mid-caps per VMA's own Inside Insight 2024. ESG report cycles, earnings-call phrase tracking, and award wins are Tier 3 enrichment signals at best \'97 they are aggressively marketed by vendors but the empirical base rates are either unpublished or indistinguishable from noise.\
Two categories that her current draft treats as strong signals are, on inspection, inverted or fluff. IC platform purchases (Staffbase, Poppulo, Workvivo, Simpplr, LumApps, Firstup, Unily) are repeatedly narrated in vendor case studies as being bought 3\'969 months after a new Head of IC arrives \'97 the purchase is a lagging indicator of a hire, not a leading one. This means the "IC platform purchase" signal should be re-purposed as a candidate-discovery signal (newly appointed Head of IC to build a relationship with) rather than a client-discovery signal (imminent hire). Engagement-survey vendor switches have the same inversion. Conference speaker rosters, CIPR Chartership awards, and ESG publication calendars are widely claimed as predictors but lack any empirical foundation; they should be disabled from the scan or demoted to weighting variables only.\
The most important commercial consequence of this empirical review is that the universe-wide 500\'961,000-company daily scan in her current draft is dramatically over-scoped. Tier 1 signals produce perhaps 20\'9640 qualifying events per month across the UK senior comms market, most of which are concentrated in her already-targeted 25 key accounts and 100 lapsed-client list. Scanning the universe every day to find them spends 60\'9670% of the API budget on false positives. The architecture should instead run a narrowly-scoped Tier 1 daily scan (her 225-entity watchlist plus RNS and Companies House UK-wide feeds filtered for CEO/Chair events at \'a3100m+ employers) and reserve weekly, batch-processed deep scans for Tier 2/3 signals on sector-stratified samples rather than the full universe.\
The system she should actually build The architectural correction is to treat Claude Code not as a universal intelligence engine but as a pipeline of narrow, cheap, cached workers orchestrated by a small number of high-leverage on-demand commands. The target shape is one CLAUDE.md file acting as operating manual, six Skills doing the heavy work, three scheduled Routines (or GitHub Actions \'97 see below) driving the continuous streams, and four slash commands for on-demand deliverables. Everything else is infrastructure: MCP integrations, dedup state, audit log, cost caps.\
The six Skills, ranked by commission impact, should be: (1) placed-candidate sensor \'97 monitors ~200 named past placements + future targets for move signals via Companies House + Coresignal job-change feed + Sales Navigator change alerts, and when a move is detected drafts a day-0 outreach email and a pre-built market-map one-pager for the old employer's successor brief plus a downstream-hires map for the new employer; (2) interim bench manager \'97 maintains a tiered 20/60/rest bench register in JobAdder, generates weekly availability check-in outreach drafts, tees up extension conversations at day 45 of every active engagement, maintains an IR35 decision-tree pre-check per role, and produces client-ready day-rate/margin calculations in one click; (3) retained pitch-pack generator \'97 for a named account, assembles a pitch pack with cost-of-vacancy ROI calc, pre-populated market map of 15\'9630 comparable companies with their current comms leaders, pre-built longlist of 5\'9610 named candidates with rationale, sector-specific salary benchmark slice, and 6-week methodology with milestone-linked fees, where every asset is auto-populated from CRM + Companies House + Coresignal; (4) reverse-match engine \'97 given one candidate, produces 10\'9615 hiring companies with named decision-makers by intersecting recent senior-comms departures, job-ad clusters, CEO transitions, IC platform purchases, and M&A activity (this is buildable and defensible; Revelio/Live Data + Sales Nav + BoardEx + Companies House is the feasible data combination at \'a390k year-one all-in); (5) fee-brief generator \'97 for a specific deal, assembles a fee-negotiation brief with named placement comparables, time-to-hire benchmarks, counter-offer rate data, notice-period norms, and a fee anchor in absolute-pounds terms rather than percent (the research shows absolute-pound anchoring consistently out-converts percent anchoring); (6) roundtable commercial engine \'97 for each of the four quarterly events, produces pre-event 1:1 prep packs per attendee (their LinkedIn, recent moves, known hiring signals, three suggested questions), a Chatham-House-compliant post-event insights report draft, and a 2\'963 week commercial-follow-up sequence per attendee.\
The three scheduled streams should be: a Tier 1 daily scan at 06:30 hitting only Companies House stream API + LSE RNS + the 225-entity watchlist (cost at Sonnet 4.6 with cached system prompts: ~\'a30.80/day); a placed-candidate sensor at 07:00 running the Skill 1 logic over ~200\'96300 past placements and hot candidates (cost: ~\'a30.70/day); and a weekly batch Tier 2/3 deep scan on Sunday overnight via Batch API (50% discount), sector-stratified into five industry shards of ~100 companies each, run through Haiku 4.5 first-pass triage then Sonnet 4.6 synthesis on the top decile, with Opus 4.7 reserved for the 10\'9620 highest-scoring events (cost: ~\'a33 per weekly run). This architecture totals ~\'a330\'9640/week in tokens steady-state \'97 well under the \'a31.50/run cap on the daily streams, and well inside a reasonable monthly budget of \'a3150\'96200 across all scans and on-demand commands.\
The four on-demand slash commands \'97 /shortlist [JD], /pitch-pack [account], /reverse-match [candidate], /fee-brief [client] \'97 are where Opus 4.7 should earn its premium. All four produce commercially material output where false positives cost money, and all four benefit from prompt caching of the stable client/candidate context across runs. Per-run costs in the $0.08\'960.13 range (well inside the $1.50 cap) are achievable for pitch-pack, reverse-match, and fee-brief with aggressive caching of the account/candidate canonical form. Shortlist over a 1,250-profile corpus requires a two-stage Haiku-screen + Sonnet-rerank pattern with Batch API for any non-urgent run, landing at \'a32\'963 per run unbatched or \'a31.50 batched \'97 this is the one place where the $1.50 cap genuinely bites and where splitting into two runs of 625 profiles each is the clean workaround.\
Claude Opus 4.7, Claude Code Routines, and the platform reality as of April 2026 Claude Opus 4.7 was released on 16 April 2026. Input is $5.00 per million tokens, output $25.00 per million, matching Opus 4.6 and 4.5 and one-third the price of Opus 4.1. The context window is 1M tokens at standard pricing (the long-context surcharge was killed in the 13 March 2026 pricing update). Prompt caching reads run at $0.50 per million tokens \'97 90% cheaper than base input \'97 and cache writes at 1.25\'d7 (5-minute TTL) or 2\'d7 (1-hour TTL) of base input. Batch API gives 50% off all token categories with minutes-to-hours async latency; it stacks with caching. The 4.7 release introduced an xhigh effort level between high and max, task budgets to cap reasoning tokens per task, server-side conversation compaction, and a new tokenizer that emits up to ~35% more tokens for the same text \'97 the stealth price increase that has to be modelled explicitly in any migrated workload. For this build the routing doctrine is: Haiku 4.5 ($1/$5) for dedup, RSS triage, cheap classifiers, voice-note cleanup; Sonnet 4.6 ($3/$15) as default workhorse for signal synthesis, structured extraction, and most scanning; Opus 4.7 ($5/$25) only for the four on-demand commands where differentiation quality pays off. This 3-tier routing is non-negotiable for staying inside the $1.50/run cap on the heavier scans.\
The platform-side infrastructure is more fragile than the user's draft assumes. Anthropic Cloud Routines did launch on 14 April 2026 as a research preview, packaging prompts + connectors into scheduled automations with triggers for cron schedules, API calls, and GitHub webhooks \'97 but the daily run caps are 5/day on Pro, 15/day on Max, 25/day on Team/Enterprise, and these are run caps, not token caps. Three continuous daily streams plus four on-demand tools will blow through the Pro cap by mid-morning. Additionally, on 4 April 2026 Anthropic ended Pro/Max subscription use for third-party agent frameworks and continuous agent workloads; any production-scale Claude Code automation now requires pay-as-you-go API billing, not a subscription seat. The practical recommendation is therefore to use Routines only for lightweight manual-trigger workflows and run the three continuous streams via GitHub Actions + Anthropic Agent SDK (free on public repos, $0.008/minute on private Linux runners) or Modal ($5\'9620/month for modest agent loads, native scheduled functions) with API-key billing. Claude Managed Agents (launched 8 April 2026) at $0.08 per session-hour are overkill for this workload unless sandboxed OAuth and multi-hour persistent sessions are genuinely required \'97 which they are not for this architecture.\
