The parallel sub-agent architecture inside Claude Code is more constrained than Anthropic's marketing suggests. There is no documented cap but community consensus and Anthropic's own guidance recommend batches of 2\'963 for reliability; power users report 5\'9610 working before rate-limit pressure on the Opus tier or orchestration complexity degrades output. For the 1,000-company deep scan the pattern is fan-out/fan-in with stratified sampling: an orchestrator splits into 10 industry-stratified shards of 100 each, 10 parallel Haiku sub-agents do cheap first-pass triage returning top-10 per shard (\'a33.20), the orchestrator fans in and 2 parallel Sonnet sub-agents rerank the 100 candidates (\'a31.30), then 2 parallel Opus sub-agents deep-dive the final 10 (\'a31.00). Total ~\'a35.50 unbatched, ~\'a32.75 via Batch API, wall time 15\'9625 minutes vs 4 hours sequential. The anti-pattern to avoid is letting sub-agents invoke each other recursively, sharing MCP connections to rate-limited APIs (serialise Unipile/Recruiter behind a token-bucket MCP), or using peer-coordinating "agent teams" which burn 7\'d7 more tokens without benefit for embarrassingly-parallel workloads.\
The delivery layer \'97 beyond the 07:00 email The 07:00 email + real-time HIGH-signal alert architecture in the current draft is fundamentally correct, but under-engineered for the commercial reality of a senior recruiter's day. The improvements that actually drive commission are: a 06:30 Tier-1 digest delivered as an email with three fixed sections \'97 move signals on her 225 entities, CEO/Chair events in her sectors, and successor opportunities on past placements \'97 each item having a one-click "draft outreach" button that triggers the /pitch-pack or successor-brief Skill; a 11:00 mid-morning dashboard refresh at web UI only (not email) showing the day's pipeline state, bench availability, and extension calendar for interims; real-time phone push notifications only for the top signal tier (>2-source corroboration, >0.8 confidence) to prevent alert fatigue; and a 17:00 voice-note inbox that captures her end-of-day debrief, runs it through AssemblyAI Universal-2 (\'a30.15/hour \'97 trivial at 11 hours/month) and a Haiku structured-extraction pass into JobAdder-ready JSON for her to review/commit the next morning. The feedback loop she already planned (gold/junk/called/won/lost/parked) should write into a simple signal-outcome log that retrains the scoring weights monthly \'97 this is where her proprietary IP accumulates and the tool compounds in value week over week.\
The single most under-rated delivery-layer improvement is a post-placement 90-day cross-sell map generated automatically for every placement. For each new Head of IC or Corp Affairs Director she places, the tool produces a one-page brief of the likely downstream hires in the 24-month window \'97 IC Business Partners, Change Comms Leads, Digital Comms Managers, Employee Experience Directors \'97 with probability estimates based on the hiring company's current comms org (scraped from the licensed Coresignal dataset) and sector norms. Top-quartile UK account directors extract 4\'967 hires from a single Head of IC placement over 24\'9636 months; median extracts 1\'962. Automating the cross-sell map is probably worth \'a3100\'96200k of incremental GP per year on its own and is almost free to build.\
Cost math at scale, with the $1.50 cap honoured Daily steady-state cost for the three continuous streams comes in at ~\'a34.50/day: contact-scan stream at \'a31.10 on Sonnet with cached context, placed-candidate monitor at \'a30.90, and the 500-company Tier-2/3 scan split into Haiku triage + Sonnet synthesis for \'a32.50 via Batch API (this is the one stream that needs to be run overnight to stay inside budget \'97 real-time is not viable). On-demand command usage averages another ~\'a31.15/day assuming one pitch-pack, one reverse-match, one fee-brief, and two shortlists per week. Monthly total sits at \'a3100\'96170 depending on batching discipline \'97 well below her implied budget and inside the $1.50/run cap on every individual scan except the 1,250-profile shortlist which must run two-stage or be split. The single largest cost-control lever is prompt caching of the stable system prompt, CLAUDE.md, tool definitions, and candidate canonical forms at 1-hour TTL for anything running more than twice per hour \'97 this alone cuts input-token cost by 60\'9680% at steady state and is the only reason the architecture fits the budget.\
The universe-wide 1,000-company daily scan the user's draft implies would run at \'a38\'9616 per execution unbatched, blowing the $1.50 cap by 5\'9610\'d7. The only way to run that scan daily within the cap is Haiku-only triage, which produces shallower signal quality than Tier-1-narrow + Sonnet synthesis on a 225-entity list. The architectural correction \'97 narrow the daily scan, run deep scans weekly via Batch \'97 is forced by the budget, and it happens to align with the empirical signal economics above.\
Compliance architecture \'97 what the ICO will actually ask for The Data (Use and Access) Act 2025 came into force on 5 February 2026 and the mandatory complaints process activates 19 June 2026; EU adequacy was renewed on 19 December 2025 through 2031. DUAA materially relaxes Article 22 for non-special-category automated decisions but imposes explicit safeguards \'97 transparency, route to contest, human-intervention-on-request, bias monitoring \'97 that are now the enforcement target. The ICO's November 2024 AI recruitment audit and April 2026 ADM-in-recruitment report both explicitly flag as the primary enforcement concern employers claiming "decision support" while in practice running solely-automated decisions without meaningful human review. For this tool that means scoring must be strictly advisory, every scored candidate must surface to Sara regardless of score, override rates must be logged and positive, and score features must be visible in the UI not just the number.\
Article 14 is the tightest legal constraint. The "within one month" clock starts on each ingestion event, not the first time you ever touched a record \'97 every new ingestion of a person into the database starts its own 30-day Article 14 clock. Because Coresignal and Bright Data enrichment typically carries a work email address, the default compliance posture must be proactive email notice within 30 days of first ingestion, not website-only notice. The disproportionate-effort exemption under Article 14(5)(b) will not hold where emails are available and the processing effect is material \'97 the Polish Bisnode precedent (220k EUR fine, upheld through 2026) and ICO's restrictive reading of the exemption for scraped-data-derived training sets both point the same way. The privacy notices of Hanson Search, Ellwood Atfield, and VMA itself are all visibly thin on source/enrichment disclosure \'97 a compliant notice for this tool needs to go materially further than the sector norm, naming Bright Data and Coresignal as sources, disclosing the categories of inferred data (tenure, move-propensity score, signal-stack), explaining the Article 22 logic, and exposing a complaints channel by 19 June 2026.\
Concretely the compliance stack needs seven components. First, a daily ingestion register that flags records due for Article 14 notice within 30 days, triggers notification, and logs delivery. Second, an LIA document for each of the four processing activities \'97 lapsed-client scanning, past-placement monitoring, openness scoring, third-party enrichment \'97 with the three-part test (purpose / necessity / balancing) documented and dated, reviewed annually. Third, a DPIA covering the end-to-end tool, because profiling + large-scale processing + invisible processing + matching/combining datasets + innovative tech each independently trigger the ICO's mandatory DPIA list. Fourth, a row-level data-lineage tag on every field (source, dataset ID, collection date, lawful basis, Art. 14 status). Fifth, an immutable append-only per-request log capturing timestamp, operator, candidate ID, prompt-template SHA, model + version, input features, output, confidence, and grounding sources \'97 this is what ICO will ask for in a complaint. Sixth, a human-review ledger logging every score-presented-to-action-taken pair with a free-text reason; a positive override rate is the single most important piece of evidence you have meaningful human review. Seventh, retention automation \'97 enrichment data deleted 12 months after last activity, past-placement monitoring capped at 24 months post-placement, a right-to-erasure process tested quarterly, and (post-June 2026) a mandatory complaints-channel acknowledgement within 30 days.\
Two categories of signal must be hard-banned from the tool regardless of how attractive they look. Protected-characteristic inference \'97 any feature that proxies for age (graduation year, tenure volatility), sex/maternity (career breaks), race (school, postcode, name), disability (employment gaps), or nationality (language patterns) \'97 is both Equality Act 2010 and ICO enforcement territory, and the November 2024 ICO audit explicitly called out name-based gender/ethnicity inference as non-compliant. Scraped LinkedIn profile deltas at 1,250-profile scale are a separate category of risk: the hiQ v LinkedIn N.D. Cal. 2022 summary judgment found hiQ had breached LinkedIn's User Agreement, the Meta v Bright Data 2024 ruling narrowly protected logged-out public scraping only, and Sales Navigator's ToS explicitly forbids recruiting use. The defensible route is Recruiter seat via Unipile plus licensed Bright Data/Coresignal datasets, with independent Article 14 notice performed by VMA \'97 vendor self-certification does not transfer liability. The 1,250-profile openness radar in her aspirational ceiling doc is buildable at 500-person scale on her own network + Revelio cohort analytics but becomes materially legally risky above that and should be capped there.\
The honest pushback on the current draft and ceiling doc Four things in the user's current architecture are over-claimed or actively counterproductive.\
The first is the universe-wide daily scan of UK companies. The signal economics do not support it \'97 the base rates on all signals except CEO transitions and job-ad velocity produce too many false positives to be actionable, and running it daily at universe scope burns 60\'9670% of the API budget on events that would appear in the 225-entity watchlist anyway within one weekly batch pass. Replacing it with a Tier-1-daily on 225 entities + Tier-2/3-weekly on stratified samples captures 90% of the commercially relevant events at 20% of the cost and 20% of the compliance surface. The ceiling-doc "predictive talent flow model" is a particular over-claim: Revelio Labs and Live Data Technologies sell cohort-level flow analytics that are real and useful, but per-person 95%-accurate quit prediction is marketing fiction \'97 academic precision/recall for external openness scoring tops out around 25\'9640% precision on a "will move in 12 months" binary, better than base rate but nowhere near the headline numbers in vendor decks.\
The second is the 1,250-candidate live profile database. Coresignal plus Sales Nav Recruiter can get you there on paper, but the maintenance cost is labour-intensive, the GDPR exposure scales non-linearly with the size of the enriched database, and \'97 most importantly \'97 the commercial uplift per additional 250 profiles past ~500 is diminishing. The CRM-depth sweet spot for a single AD-level consultant in UK senior comms is 500 actively-scored profiles + ~2,000 light-touch metadata records, not 1,250 deeply enriched ones. The difference is genuine compliance exposure, materially lower cost, and no commercial downside.\
The third is the voice-note chief of staff and custom live dashboard in the ceiling doc \'97 these are achievable but they are mid-priority infrastructure, not commission drivers. Build them in month 2\'963, not week 1. The psychological decision-maker profiles and competitor intelligence layer are the two ceiling-doc items to be most skeptical of: the first drifts into protected-characteristic-inference territory if done carelessly, and the second has historically produced low ROI for boutique recruiters versus the public data already surfaced by Coresignal + BoardEx + Sales Nav.\
